

Trump signed Executive Order 13769, the "travel ban," on Friday, January 27th, 2017. The Executive Order suspended the U.S. Refugee Admissions Program for 120 days, suspended the admission of Syrian refugees indefinitely, and, most notably, blocked entry of all travel into the United States of non-citizens from Iran, Iraq, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria, and Yemen (with minor exceptions) for 90 days. Trump signed the order to be effective immediately with little warning, notably without clear direction to officials and officers responsible for implementing the ban in the DHS, and without notifying lawyers who would be responsible for defending the ban in court at DOJ. The ban led to chaos, confusion, and legal challenges almost as soon as it was signed. On Monday, January 30th, Trump fired acting attorney general Sally Yates a few hours after she directed the DOJ not to defend the ban in court.




