[TODO: be more specific of what exactly ban did]

On January 27th, 2017, Trump signed Executive Order 13769, putting the travel ban into effect the moment it was signed. The immediate result has been described as "global chaos."

Because the ban was effective immediately, every person affected by the Executive Order who were currently in transit or about to travel to the United States were immediately considered barred from entry. The order canceled the visas of 60,000 - 100,000 foreign nationals who had until that moment allowed to travel to the United States. Of these, 1,200 visa-holders were denied boarding flights between January 27 and February 2. At least 109 travelers had already boarded and were subsequently detained at U.S. ports of entry, and a portion of these were sent back to their country they flew in from or attempted to be sent back. These last two groups in particular were caught by surprise by the ban: as one attorney put it in a January 28th hearing, "They took off before the executive order was signed. They landed after."


https://law.yale.edu/system/files/area/clinic/document/2017.01.28_emergency_motion_for_stay.pdf
	MR. GELERNT: -- they can't give assurances and we also just were told that the government is threatening to put someone back on a plane at 9:20 and we don't even know what's going on around the country. There are so many people -- and so we are here, what we think is a fairly modest request to the Court, to just keep things in place until both sides can brief it.

	...We think we have the better of it but certainly on irreparable harm ...They took off before the executive order was signed. They landed after. And so, they were in a horrible position. They were on U.S. soil and they certainly can't be sent back without, at a minimum, an asylum hearing and a Convention Against Torture -- I mean that is basic law.

	THE COURT: Do you have a sense of how many people we're talking about? that was another question that I had.

	MR. GELERNT: Yeah. You know, your Honor, we believe that it's upwards of a hundred to 200.


Travelers were not the only ones caught by surprise by the ban. According to the DHS Inspector General, leadership of Customs and Border Protection (CBP), primarily responsible for implementing the ban, had "virtually no warning" of the order's scope or that it was coming at all. According to then-Secretary of Homeland Security John Kelly, the Trump administration had kept the executive order on a "close hold basis" and so it was not distributed widely:


https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LxKJ0FEoFqY&t=23m50s
	DHS Kelly: I did know it was under development. I had an opportunity to look at at least two--as I recollect--drafts as it got closer to Friday. Again I don't exactly know other than some of my legal shop representatives were involved, I would imagine some, on the landing team, I would imagine some of them. But the point is it came to the department it was you know on a close hold basis meaning we didn't distribute it to everyone in the department...


https://www.oig.dhs.gov/file/4678/download?token=kEDXANI_
	We found:

	* The leadership of CBP, the OHS entity primarily responsible for implementation of the order, had virtually no warning that the EO was to be issued or of the scope of the order, and was caught by surprise. Indeed, during the early period of implementation of the order, neither CBP nor the Department was sure of the answers to basic questions as to the scope of the order ...CBP was unable to issue definitive guidance in the early days of implementation of the EO, which contributed to significant delays at the ports of entry.


The DHS OIG's investigation into the travel ban found that CBP could not get answers on "basic questions" about the order from the Trump administration and so could not be sure how the order was to be implemented the first few days the ban was in effect.

The importance of this point should not be underestimated. There are questions about the ban's implementation who's answer would be crucial to it's survival in the courts: Should travelers in-transit at the time of the order be detained and sent back? What should be done to respect their due-process rights? Does the order apply to lawful permanent residents? And should U.S. residents be barred from returning home?

The answers to these questions, at least as interpreted on-the-fly by various employees of CBP, can be inferred from court documents and media reports:


http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/30/politics/trump-travel-ban-q-and-a/
	This is the "extreme vetting" Trump promised during the campaign, but it still seems to have caught folks by surprise.


